title: CSS - an introduction
author: Cherilynn Plinck
description: CSS, or Cascading Style Sheets, is a style sheet language used for describing the presentation of a web page written in HTML or XML. CSS is used to control the layout, typography, colors, and other visual aspects of a website, allowing web designers to create visually appealing and engaging websites that are optimized for different devices and screen sizes. CSS works by associating style rules with HTML elements. A style rule consists of a selector, which specifies which HTML elements the rule applies to, and a set of declarations, which specify the visual properties that should be applied to those elements. CSS also allows for the creation of classes and IDs, which can be used to apply styles to specific elements or groups of elements within a web page. One of the key benefits of CSS is its ability to separate the content of a web page from its presentation. By keeping the HTML and CSS in separate files, it becomes easier to make changes to the visual design of a website without affecting its content, making it easier to maintain and update the website over time. CSS also includes a range of advanced features, such as media queries, which allow designers to create responsive designs that are optimized for different devices and screen sizes. CSS also supports animations and transitions, allowing for the creation of dynamic and interactive web pages. CSS is constantly evolving, with new features and specifications being added over time. The latest version of CSS is CSS3, which includes a wide range of new features and improvements over previous versions. Overall, CSS is a crucial technology for creating modern and visually appealing websites. By separating the presentation of a website from its content, CSS makes it easier to create and maintain websites that are optimized for different devices and screen sizes, while also allowing for the creation of dynamic and interactive web pages.

title: HTML - an introduction
author: Chantal Jacketts
description: HTML, or Hypertext Markup Language, is a markup language used for creating web pages and other documents that can be displayed in a web browser. It is a core technology of the World Wide Web and is used in conjunction with other technologies such as CSS and JavaScript to create interactive and visually appealing websites. HTML consists of a series of elements, which are used to define the structure and content of a web page. These elements include headings, paragraphs, lists, images, links, forms, and tables, among others. HTML documents are written using plain text and are saved with the .html or .htm file extension. One of the key features of HTML is its ability to create hyperlinks between web pages, allowing users to navigate between different pages on the web. HTML also allows for the inclusion of multimedia content such as images, audio, and video, making it possible to create engaging and interactive web pages. Another important aspect of HTML is its ability to be accessed by screen readers and other assistive technologies, making it an important tool for creating accessible websites that can be used by people with disabilities. HTML has evolved over time, with newer versions of the language introducing new features and functionality. The latest version of HTML is HTML5, which includes new elements and attributes for creating more advanced web applications, as well as improved support for multimedia content. Overall, HTML is a crucial technology for creating web pages and other digital content that can be displayed in a web browser. It provides the basic structure and content of a web page, allowing developers to create engaging and interactive websites that can be accessed by people around the world.

title: JavaScript - an introduction
author: Paulette Withers
description: JavaScript is a versatile and powerful programming language that has become a staple of modern web development. Originally created in the mid-1990s by Netscape Communications, it has since become one of the most widely used programming languages on the web. JavaScript is primarily known for its use in creating interactive and dynamic user interfaces on the frontend of web applications. However, over the years, it has evolved from being just a frontend language to a full-stack language capable of developing both frontend and backend components of web applications. One of the major reasons for JavaScript's popularity is its ability to run on both the client-side and server-side. Node.js, a platform built on top of the V8 JavaScript engine, allows developers to run JavaScript code on the server-side, enabling them to write code in a single language across the entire application stack. This can result in faster development times, easier maintenance, and more streamlined workflows. JavaScript has also become a popular and well-supported language, with a vast ecosystem of resources and tools available to help developers build full-stack applications. This includes libraries and frameworks like Angular or Vue.js, which provide powerful tools for building complex and dynamic user interfaces. In addition to its versatility and popularity, JavaScript is also constantly evolving. New features and improvements are added regularly, with the latest version of JavaScript being ECMAScript 2021 (ES6). This version includes new features such as logical assignment operators, promise.any(), and numeric separators.JavaScript is a flexible language that can be used in a wide variety of applications, from simple animations to complex web applications. It is an essential tool for creating modern and interactive websites and web applications, and its popularity shows no signs of slowing down. As the web continues to evolve, JavaScript will undoubtedly continue to play a critical role in its development.

title: Responsive design with Bootstrap
author: Elene Janczyk
description: Bootstrap is a popular front-end framework used for creating responsive websites and applications. It was created by Twitter and is now maintained by the Bootstrap team. One of its main advantages is that it provides pre-designed UI components and layout templates, which can save developers a lot of time when creating new web projects. Bootstrap's responsive design capabilities ensure that websites and applications look and function well on a variety of devices, from large desktops to small mobile screens. It uses a grid system of rows and columns, which allows developers to create a consistent and cohesive layout across all devices. Bootstrap also uses SCSS for its CSS pre-processing, which allows developers to write cleaner and more organized CSS code. SCSS provides features like variables and mixins, which can speed up development by allowing developers to reuse common styles across multiple components. One of the main advantages of using Bootstrap is its large and active community. This community provides a wealth of resources, including documentation, tutorials, and plugins, which can help developers get up and running quickly. Additionally, because Bootstrap is so widely used, it is more likely that other developers will be familiar with it, making collaboration on projects easier. However, because it is so popular, many websites and applications built with it can end up looking similar. In summary, Bootstrap is a powerful and widely-used front-end framework that can save developers time and effort when creating responsive and visually appealing websites and applications. Its pre-designed UI components, responsive design capabilities, and use of SCSS make it a popular choice among developers. However, its popularity can also lead to websites and applications that look too similar, and it can be easy to overuse its pre-designed components, leading to cluttered and overwhelming designs.
